I want history lessons,

00:47:59.461 --> 00:48:01.840
1, just because I think
there's this huge gap

00:48:01.840 --> 00:48:03.968
between the news and what goes
on in history class right now,

00:48:03.968 --> 00:48:05.796
where the news is these
30-second sound bites,

00:48:05.796 --> 00:48:07.300
and history class, you start off

00:48:07.300 --> 00:48:08.890
with Mohenjo-daro and Harappa.

00:48:08.890 --> 00:48:12.278
If you're lucky, you
might get to World War 2.

00:48:12.278 --> 00:48:14.656
There's this huge gap between that and ...

00:48:14.656 --> 00:48:15.893
I don't think that happens
here at Castilleja.

00:48:15.893 --> 00:48:18.304
I never got beyond World
War 2 in my history.

00:48:18.304 --> 00:48:21.179
That leaves this huge
gap in why is the world

00:48:21.179 --> 00:48:22.116
the way it is right now?

00:48:22.116 --> 00:48:25.059
Actually, I would like
to do a little 10 minutes

00:48:25.059 --> 00:48:27.251
on Israel and Palestine conflict,

00:48:27.251 --> 00:48:28.520
10 minutes on Indian ...

00:48:28.520 --> 00:48:30.138
Obviously, these are very touchy issues,

00:48:30.138 --> 00:48:32.145
and I'm going to have a
lot of caveats out there.

00:48:32.145 --> 00:48:33.652
I actually have a whole set of videos

00:48:33.652 --> 00:48:35.225
on intelligent design and evolution.

00:48:35.225 --> 00:48:38.302
I keep [unintelligible].

00:48:38.317 --> 00:48:39.730
I don't want to skew your opinion.

00:48:39.730 --> 00:48:42.472
But anyway, I do intend to do that.

00:48:42.472 --> 00:48:45.659
I do want to do grammar.
I want to do everything.

00:48:45.659 --> 00:48:48.448
I think all of y'all should join in.

00:48:50.110 --> 00:48:51.354
Female: Sorry.

00:48:51.354 --> 00:48:55.399
Female: How do you know so
much on all of these subjects?

00:48:55.399 --> 00:48:56.795
(laughter)

00:48:56.795 --> 00:48:58.642
Sal: My wife would be
rolling her eyes right now.

00:48:58.642 --> 00:49:03.822
(laughter) There's a small set of things

00:49:03.822 --> 00:49:07.216
that I do know based on my background.

00:49:07.216 --> 00:49:11.953
I was a mathlete in high school,
on some level. (laughter)

00:49:11.953 --> 00:49:16.541
Other things, like biology,
I took the courses.

00:49:16.541 --> 00:49:18.889
I got an A in the course,
but that doesn't mean

00:49:18.889 --> 00:49:21.072
I'm an expert on biology.

00:49:21.072 --> 00:49:23.456
What I do is ... and this
is what's really fun for me.

00:49:23.456 --> 00:49:25.800
The other aspect that really motivates me

00:49:25.800 --> 00:49:27.463
is I get to sit and learn things

00:49:27.463 --> 00:49:28.918
when I never learned them before.

00:49:28.918 --> 00:49:33.367
For example, I did some videos
on entropy a few weeks ago.

00:49:33.367 --> 00:49:35.258
Entropy was something that
I never understood properly

00:49:35.258 --> 00:49:36.004
in high school.

00:49:36.004 --> 00:49:37.752
I could write the right words on the exam,

00:49:37.752 --> 00:49:40.532
but I never quite
understood what it meant.

00:49:40.532 --> 00:49:42.051
I literally pondered it for 2 weeks.

00:49:42.051 --> 00:49:43.884
I would call up my
thermodynamics professor friends

00:49:43.884 --> 00:49:45.267
at Standford and MIT.

00:49:45.267 --> 00:49:47.438
I was like, "Let's have a
conversation about entropy."

00:49:47.438 --> 00:49:49.653
We would do that. Then, over the
course of time [unintelligible],

00:49:49.653 --> 00:49:50.951
I was like, "Okay. Now I get entropy,"

00:49:50.951 --> 00:49:52.522
and I would make the videos on them.

00:49:52.522 --> 00:49:54.354
A lot of it, it's a
learning process for me,

00:49:54.354 --> 00:49:56.169
and that's what makes it so much fun.

00:49:57.246 --> 00:49:59.203
Female: Mr. Khan. Can you repeat
the questions that are asked?

00:49:59.203 --> 00:50:00.651
Sal: Oh. Sorry. Just so y'all know,

00:50:00.651 --> 00:50:02.465
the question was, "How do I know so much?"

00:50:02.465 --> 00:50:06.556
(laughter) That was the ... Yeah.

00:50:06.556 --> 00:50:08.497
Female: When exactly
did your YouTube videos

00:50:08.497 --> 00:50:11.283
become the brand, Khan Academy?

00:50:11.283 --> 00:50:13.093
When was that transition?

00:50:13.093 --> 00:50:14.598
Sal: Oh, you're one of the few people

00:50:14.613 --> 00:50:16.657
that refer to it as a
brand, but that's exciting.

00:50:16.657 --> 00:50:18.501
The question is, "When
did the YouTube videos

00:50:18.501 --> 00:50:22.105
"become the brand, Khan Academy?"

00:50:22.105 --> 00:50:25.416
I think I was at a birthday
party for a friend.

00:50:25.416 --> 00:50:26.838
He was the first person to say,

00:50:26.838 --> 00:50:28.209
"What you're doing with your cousins,

00:50:28.209 --> 00:50:29.942
"this is actually something
that could be generally useful.

00:50:29.942 --> 00:50:31.781
"You should do something with it,

00:50:31.781 --> 00:50:33.512
"make it into some type
of an organization."

00:50:33.512 --> 00:50:35.935
The Khan Academy is a
non-for-profit organization,

00:50:35.935 --> 00:50:37.312
but when he told me that,

00:50:37.312 --> 00:50:40.200
that was the first time that
I thought about the idea,

00:50:40.200 --> 00:50:42.098
"Wow, this could be a virtual school,

00:50:42.098 --> 00:50:43.903
"or this could be something."

00:50:43.903 --> 00:50:45.608
Since it's a nonprofit organization,

00:50:45.608 --> 00:50:47.153
I was like, "Well, gee.
There's no ownership.

00:50:47.153 --> 00:50:48.907
"How do I make sure they
don't fire me one day?"

00:50:48.907 --> 00:50:50.769
I said, "Well, let me
name it after myself."

00:50:50.769 --> 00:50:57.397
(laughter)

00:50:57.397 --> 00:50:59.998
Female: How'd you develop a curriculum

00:50:59.998 --> 00:51:02.282
for each course that could be used

00:51:02.282 --> 00:51:05.696
for people all over the
world [unintelligible]?

00:51:05.696 --> 00:51:08.424
Sal: The question was, "How
did I develop a curriculum?"

00:51:08.424 --> 00:51:09.562
I actually get a lot of ...

00:51:09.562 --> 00:51:10.796
I actually talked to
the State of California,

00:51:10.796 --> 00:51:12.198
and that's the first question they asked,

00:51:12.198 --> 00:51:13.577
"Where's the curriculum come from?"

00:51:13.577 --> 00:51:15.486
It initially started very organically.

00:51:15.486 --> 00:51:17.835
It was math and science as I had known it,

00:51:17.835 --> 00:51:20.446
with the theory being if I'm able

00:51:20.446 --> 00:51:22.940
to convey that understanding
in those connections,

00:51:22.940 --> 00:51:24.515
that that's a good understanding.

00:51:24.515 --> 00:51:27.745
YouTube had 10-minute time
limits on me, initially.

00:51:27.745 --> 00:51:30.478
That was super fortuitous because
it forced me to 10 minutes.

00:51:30.478 --> 00:51:32.241
What that allowed me to
do is make the concepts

00:51:32.241 --> 00:51:36.030
very granular and short.

00:51:36.030 --> 00:51:38.126
Miami Dade County has actually used them

00:51:38.126 --> 00:51:39.491
for teacher training.

00:51:39.491 --> 00:51:41.814
It's very easy to map it to
almost any curriculum now

00:51:41.814 --> 00:51:45.597
because the videos just cover
one small concept at a time.

00:51:45.597 --> 00:51:47.616
You could say, "Oh. The standard 2.3.2

00:51:47.616 --> 00:51:50.531
"in the California Standards,
that's these 4 videos."

00:51:50.531 --> 00:51:52.614
I don't have ... but some of
the things I am doing now,

00:51:52.614 --> 00:51:53.945
I do look at textbooks.

00:51:53.945 --> 00:51:57.046
I do look at what the AP
Curriculum, the standards are,

00:51:57.046 --> 00:51:58.947
so I do try to make it so it's useful

00:51:58.947 --> 00:52:01.531
for tests that people are
going to have to take.

00:52:03.285 --> 00:52:05.372
Up there, in the [black].

00:52:05.372 --> 00:52:07.177
Female: How do you make it available

00:52:07.177 --> 00:52:09.233
to people [unintelligible]?

00:52:09.233 --> 00:52:11.551
Sal: The question is, "How
do I make it available

00:52:11.551 --> 00:52:14.482
"to people who don't speak English?"

00:52:14.482 --> 00:52:17.084
English is the only language I speak well.

00:52:17.084 --> 00:52:20.986
I can laughably speak
Hindi [unintelligible],

00:52:20.986 --> 00:52:22.755
but that wouldn't do the job.

00:52:22.755 --> 00:52:24.234
That's an excellent question.

00:52:24.234 --> 00:52:25.556
People have come out of the wood works.

00:52:25.556 --> 00:52:27.231
This is another thing I
actually forgot to talk about.

00:52:27.231 --> 00:52:28.368
People have come out of the wood works

00:52:28.368 --> 00:52:30.723
over the last 3 months to
start translating the videos.

00:52:30.723 --> 00:52:32.403
Because, in the videos,
you don't see my face,

00:52:32.403 --> 00:52:34.281
the translations work really well.

00:52:34.281 --> 00:52:35.545
They look like they were natively spoken.

00:52:35.545 --> 00:52:37.736
There's actually a chemistry
teacher in Uruguay,

00:52:37.736 --> 00:52:40.275
who has started translating
the chemistry videos.

00:52:40.275 --> 00:52:43.232
He set up a "Khan Academy
en Espanol" channel.

00:52:43.232 --> 00:52:45.017
It's just happening organically.

00:52:45.017 --> 00:52:49.093
Translators are [unintelligible]
Polish, German ...

00:52:49.093 --> 00:52:51.128
Once again, I'm doing nothing.

00:52:51.128 --> 00:52:52.737
All I'm just saying is, "Go ahead,"

00:52:52.737 --> 00:52:55.186
and people are translating it.

00:52:55.186 --> 00:52:56.776
Female: Do you still
find that there are some

00:52:56.776 --> 00:52:58.432
children who need personal tuition?

00:52:58.432 --> 00:53:00.327
Are you still doing that at all?

00:53:00.327 --> 00:53:04.143
Sal: I am no longer directly interfering.

00:53:04.143 --> 00:53:05.655
The question is, "Do I
find that there's still

00:53:05.655 --> 00:53:07.909
"some children who need personal tuition?"

00:53:07.909 --> 00:53:09.389
Kind of what I was used to doing

00:53:09.389 --> 00:53:11.159
with Nadia and her brothers.

00:53:11.159 --> 00:53:14.226
I still call them up and check in on them,

00:53:14.226 --> 00:53:17.310
but I haven't been doing
that 1-on-1 session

00:53:17.310 --> 00:53:18.332
with them anymore.

00:53:18.332 --> 00:53:19.561
They're all in high school now.

00:53:19.561 --> 00:53:21.543
They've, I think, gotten over
their hurdles, but I' not.

00:53:21.543 --> 00:53:23.738
I think ... I don't want to make it sound

00:53:23.738 --> 00:53:25.388
like this solves all the problems.

00:53:25.388 --> 00:53:27.264
I think this gets a lot of
problems out of the way,

00:53:27.264 --> 00:53:29.937
so that the personal time with a teacher

00:53:29.937 --> 00:53:31.482
or a tutor can be a lot more productive.

00:53:31.482 --> 00:53:33.307
I'm sure there are people
who can always benefit

00:53:33.307 --> 00:53:36.188
from that personal instruction.

00:53:36.188 --> 00:53:40.074
Yeah. Right here. How about
you in front? Yeah. You.

00:53:40.074 --> 00:53:41.944
Female: When you're making the videos,

00:53:41.944 --> 00:53:43.689
how do decide which concept

00:53:43.689 --> 00:53:45.383
you're going to cover next?

00:53:45.383 --> 00:53:47.192
Sal: The question is,
"When I make the videos,

00:53:47.192 --> 00:53:50.929
"how do I decide what
concept I cover next?"

00:53:50.929 --> 00:53:52.426
Some of it ... I get emails all the time,

00:53:52.426 --> 00:53:53.174
and I take requests.

00:53:53.174 --> 00:53:54.258
I'm telling this to all of y'all.

00:53:54.258 --> 00:53:56.280
If y'all have a
particularly hairy problem,

00:53:56.280 --> 00:53:59.665
that I haven't ... Send
it to me, seriously.

00:53:59.665 --> 00:54:02.586
I literally put your email up,
and we'll do a video on it,

00:54:02.586 --> 00:54:05.537
and it'll be up there.

00:54:05.537 --> 00:54:10.747
I do take requests, but
a lot of it is my mood.

00:54:10.747 --> 00:54:12.512
I'm doing this almost out of ...

00:54:12.512 --> 00:54:14.841
It's fun for me, so I
do what's interesting,

00:54:14.841 --> 00:54:17.489
where I think a lot of people
would find value from it.

00:54:17.489 --> 00:54:19.950
The simple answer is,
what I feel like teaching

00:54:19.950 --> 00:54:22.150
is what I teach, which is
a huge luxury, I think.

00:54:23.457 --> 00:54:24.569
Oh, you.

00:54:24.569 --> 00:54:26.125
Female: Where do you see
the Khan Academy going

00:54:26.125 --> 00:54:27.823
in the next 5 or 10 years?

00:54:27.823 --> 00:54:30.187
Sal: Yeah, where I see it going.

00:54:30.187 --> 00:54:32.095
I could talk for another hour.

00:54:35.371 --> 00:54:37.196
Right now, there's the videos.

00:54:37.196 --> 00:54:38.529
I intend to keep making videos,

00:54:38.529 --> 00:54:39.700
several hundred a year.

00:54:39.700 --> 00:54:41.285
I really want to cover everything.

00:54:41.285 --> 00:54:43.720
Oh, the question was, "Where
do I see Khan Academy going

00:54:43.720 --> 00:54:45.300
"over the next 5, 10 years?"

00:54:45.300 --> 00:54:46.947
I'm going to keep making videos.

00:54:46.947 --> 00:54:48.315
The software piece, I want to build out.

00:54:48.315 --> 00:54:50.283
I'm talking to some philanthropic groups

00:54:50.283 --> 00:54:53.385
about potentially being able to
hire a small team of engineers

00:54:53.385 --> 00:54:56.456
to build out the software
so people can practice,

00:54:56.456 --> 00:54:58.898
and we can get data on what
works and what doesn't work.

00:54:58.898 --> 00:55:02.264
Then, this actually ties into world peace.

00:55:02.264 --> 00:55:04.696
What I want to do is overlay
that with the community,

00:55:04.696 --> 00:55:06.779
where people are using the vidoes.

00:55:06.779 --> 00:55:08.403
People are using the software,

00:55:08.403 --> 00:55:09.737
but if they still don't get it,

00:55:09.737 --> 00:55:12.285
the site knows what they're
having difficulty with,

00:55:12.285 --> 00:55:14.369
and it can match them
up with someone else.

00:55:14.369 --> 00:55:16.294
You are a 9th grader in [Taron].

00:55:16.294 --> 00:55:19.341
You have trouble with
systems of equations.

00:55:19.341 --> 00:55:24.145
There's a brilliant teacher
who is a 10th grader,

00:55:24.145 --> 00:55:26.532
in Tel Aviv, and we'll
connect the two of you.

00:55:26.532 --> 00:55:27.912
Y'all will have a session.

00:55:27.912 --> 00:55:29.449
Y'all will talk about mathematics,

00:55:29.449 --> 00:55:31.445
and respect each other, and do well.

00:55:31.445 --> 00:55:33.058
As you can imagine, over time,

00:55:33.058 --> 00:55:35.636
that can foster a whole
set of other things.

00:55:35.636 --> 00:55:37.119
Actually, I'm talking to
these philanthropic groups

00:55:37.119 --> 00:55:39.551
because there's potential
of going to rural villages

00:55:39.551 --> 00:55:41.234
where you can't find algebra teachers,

00:55:41.234 --> 00:55:43.697
where students, even if you build them

00:55:43.697 --> 00:55:45.250
the best school on the planet,

00:55:45.250 --> 00:55:46.303
and you give them the teachers,

00:55:46.303 --> 00:55:47.231
they're not going to show up

00:55:47.231 --> 00:55:48.644
because they have to
help out their families

00:55:48.644 --> 00:55:51.788
during the harvest, or
work, or whatever else.

00:55:52.957 --> 00:55:55.010
The idea is really have
a school-in-the-box,

00:55:55.010 --> 00:55:56.565
where kids can learn on their own time,

00:55:56.565 --> 00:55:58.312
and then the philanthropic group

00:55:58.312 --> 00:55:59.777
can actually take a step back,

00:55:59.777 --> 00:56:01.351
and the data comes back to them,

00:56:01.351 --> 00:56:03.644
and see what the kids in the
villages are actually doing.

00:56:03.644 --> 00:56:07.107
I envision this world-wide virtual school.

00:56:07.107 --> 00:56:08.159
That's my dream.

00:56:08.159 --> 00:56:09.866
It might even have physical incarnations.

00:56:09.866 --> 00:56:11.656
But, the physical
incarnations are just places

00:56:11.656 --> 00:56:16.772
to plug into this world-wide
school that spans all continents.

00:56:16.772 --> 00:56:18.842
That's my dream.

00:56:19.793 --> 00:56:22.680
Any ... right there.

00:56:22.680 --> 00:56:24.297
Female: Have you ever felt like,

00:56:24.297 --> 00:56:25.981
with all the [unintelligible] and stuff,

00:56:25.981 --> 00:56:28.827
that you need to hire people to
help you with [unintelligible]?

00:56:28.827 --> 00:56:29.917
Sal: I have, many ... The question is

00:56:29.917 --> 00:56:32.958
"Have I ever thought that I need
to hire someone to help me?"

00:56:33.988 --> 00:56:37.440
The answer is, yes. I have.

00:56:38.701 --> 00:56:41.674
Right now, it's being
funded by the Salman Khan

00:56:41.674 --> 00:56:45.500
Bank of America checking
account, (laughter)

00:56:45.500 --> 00:56:50.076
and they're pretty stingy. (laughter)

00:56:50.076 --> 00:56:51.769
I do want to hire people,

00:56:51.769 --> 00:56:53.144
especially on the software side.

00:56:53.144 --> 00:56:54.643
I've actually thought
about bringing other people

00:56:54.643 --> 00:56:57.172
for on the content side, even in English.

00:56:57.172 --> 00:56:58.968
It's actually harder than I thought.

00:56:58.968 --> 00:57:02.159
I have a lot of friends who would
probably be brilliant instructors,

00:57:02.159 --> 00:57:04.306
but something about the YouTube format,

00:57:04.306 --> 00:57:05.334
they start to freeze up.

00:57:05.334 --> 00:57:06.736
I think one of the big values about it

00:57:06.736 --> 00:57:07.892
is when I started making this,

00:57:07.892 --> 00:57:09.133
I wasn't getting paid to do it.

00:57:09.133 --> 00:57:10.966
It wasn't stressed about it.

00:57:10.966 --> 00:57:12.287
I was like, "This is for Nadia and Armand.

00:57:12.287 --> 00:57:13.866
"They're going to take what I give them."

00:57:13.866 --> 00:57:16.293
(laughter) I literally ...
I'm answering the phone.

00:57:16.293 --> 00:57:17.904
I'm talking to telemarketers on some

00:57:17.904 --> 00:57:19.041
of these early videos.

00:57:19.041 --> 00:57:21.038
It has this very ...

00:57:21.038 --> 00:57:23.716
You hear my wife yelling at me
sometimes in the background.

00:57:23.716 --> 00:57:24.676
(laughter) It's really low-key,

00:57:24.676 --> 00:57:27.171
but I think that's why
it's connected with people.

00:57:28.509 --> 00:57:31.525
The answer is I would like
to hire up a small team,

00:57:31.525 --> 00:57:33.781
probably 5 or 10 people, eventually.

00:57:34.529 --> 00:57:36.622
Oh, our last question.
Right there in the back.

00:57:36.622 --> 00:57:39.599
Female: Have you ever considered
visiting the rural areas

00:57:39.599 --> 00:57:43.334
where your videos are being
watched [unintelligible]?

00:57:43.334 --> 00:57:45.306
Sal: The question is, "Have
I ever considered visiting

00:57:45.306 --> 00:57:49.408
"the rural areas where the videos
are being watched firsthand?"

00:57:49.408 --> 00:57:51.695
I would love to do that.

00:57:51.695 --> 00:57:53.608
I have an irrational fear of flying,

00:57:53.608 --> 00:57:55.027
which I need to get over.

00:57:55.027 --> 00:57:58.128
Other than that, I would love to.

00:58:00.820 --> 00:58:02.295
In particular, the group in Uganda,

00:58:02.295 --> 00:58:03.472
they seem to be doing tremendously.

00:58:03.472 --> 00:58:05.807
They send me pictures all of the time,

00:58:05.807 --> 00:58:08.668
but nothing would be more
exciting than to do that.

00:58:08.668 --> 00:58:13.045
Actually, my mother's village,
which is outside of Calcutta,

00:58:13.045 --> 00:58:15.403
I would love to ...
they're apparently using it

00:58:15.403 --> 00:58:17.517
on some level over there as well.

00:58:17.517 --> 00:58:18.838
